<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Morphological characters are in accordance with the description of 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. albatrossianum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="albatrossianum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. albatrossianum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The 18S sequence matches three genera within the subfamily 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zevina" authorityYear="1978" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Arcoscalpellinae">Arcoscalpellinae</taxonomicName>
Zevina, 1978, while the closest match (85% similarity) for the COI sequence is to another species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zevina" authorityYear="1978" class="Echinoidea" family="Scalpellidae" genus="Catherinum" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Catherinum" order="Aspidodiadematoida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Catherinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Like, 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. novaezelandiae" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="novaezelandiae">C. cf. novaezelandiae</taxonomicName>
it differs morphologically from 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. tortilum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="tortilum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. tortilum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, reported from the CCZ by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3297.1.2" author="Poltarukha, OP" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="34 - 40" refId="B79" refString="Poltarukha, OP, Mel'Nik, VF, 2012. New records of deep-sea barnacles (Cirripedia: Thoracica: Scalpelliformes) from the Clarion-Clipperton region, Pacific Ocean. Zootaxa 3297: 34 - 40, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3297.1.2" title="New records of deep-sea barnacles (Cirripedia: Thoracica: Scalpelliformes) from the Clarion-Clipperton region, Pacific Ocean." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3297.1.2" volume="3297" year="2012">
Poltarukha and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Mel’Nik">Mel'Nik</normalizedToken>
(2012)
</bibRefCitation>
, in the form of the inframedian latus. The type locality of 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. albatrossianum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="albatrossianum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. albatrossianum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is off Cape Hatteras, in the northwest Atlantic, at ~ 3740 m depth, but it has been reported for the North Atlantic, Gulf of Mexico, and Indian Ocean between 760 and 4180 m depth (
<bibRefCitation author="Zevina, GB" journalOrPublisher="Invertebrate Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="101 - 111" publicationUrl="http://oceanrep.geomar.de/id/eprint/28024" refId="B105" refString="Zevina, GB, Poltarukha, OP, 2014. Deep-sea fauna of European seas: An annotated species check-list of benthic invertebrates living deeper than 2000 m in the seas bordering Europe. Cirripedia. Invertebrate Zoology 11: 101 - 111, http://oceanrep.geomar.de/id/eprint/28024" title="Deep-sea fauna of European seas: An annotated species check-list of benthic invertebrates living deeper than 2000 m in the seas bordering Europe. Cirripedia." url="http://oceanrep.geomar.de/id/eprint/28024" volume="11" year="2014">Zevina and Poltarukha 2014</bibRefCitation>
). The original description states that the species lacks a rostrum, however, a minute rostrum is present in the specimen examined herein. This in addition to the documented range of this species is the reason for the use of cf. in the identification.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Specimen was collected in a muddy abyssal area of APEI 7, at 4874 m depth. It was attached to a glass sponge stalk (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Trianguloscalpellum gigas (Hoek, 1883). Specimen CCZ _ 074: A in situ photograph, attached to a glass sponge stalk B left C and right lateral views. Scale bars: 5 cm (A); 1 mm (B, C). Image attribution: Durden and Smith (A), Hosie (B, C). Arrows indicate position of T. gigas (specimen CCZ _ 074; lower, yellow) and Catherinum cf. albatrossianum (specimen CCZ _ 073; upper, green)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1113.82172.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/716331" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">5A</figureCitation>
; upper, green arrow), along with another barnacle (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hoek" baseAuthorityYear="1883" class="Maxillopoda" family="Scalpellidae" genus="Trianguloscalpellum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trianguloscalpellum gigas" order="Actiniaria" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gigas">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Trianguloscalpellum gigas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, specimen CCZ_074; lower, yellow arrow), and an anemone (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zevina" authorityYear="1978" class="Maxillopoda" family="Scalpellidae" genus="Trianguloscalpellum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Actiniaria" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="superFamily" superFamily="Metridioidea">Metridioidea</taxonomicName>
stet. CCZ_072; specimen CCZ_072). It had hydrozoans and two serpulid polychaetes attached to it.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comparisons">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comparison with image-based catalogue.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
A very similar morphotype (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zevina" authorityYear="1978" class="Echinoidea" family="Scalpellidae" genus="Catherinum" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Catherinum" order="Aspidodiadematoida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Catherinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. indet., ART_032) has been encountered (e.g., large specimens&gt; 3 cm in length) in seabed image surveys conducted across the eastern CCZ and in abyssal areas of the Kiribati EEZ.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
